<b>Goodair</b>, a nickname from Middle English <i>god(e)</i>, <i>gu(o)d</i> ‘good’ + <i>heir(e)</i>, <i>(h)air(e)</i> ‘heir’."]},{"name":"Gowers","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Liam.","English (Essex and Suffolk): variant of   Gower  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Gurr","meanings":["German: derisive nickname for a useless person or a wicked woman, from Middle High German <i>gurre</i> ‘bad mare’.","English (Kent and Middlesex): variant of   Gower   or   Gore  ."]},{"name":"Jowers","meanings":["English (Essex and Suffolk): variant of   Gower  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Goward","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Gower  , with excrescent <i>-d</i>."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Gower was born about 1425, her father, Gower, was 27 and her mother, Mrs Gower, was 27. She married Henry Thompson in 1442. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"ABT. 1425–":"umbes 1425–Surnud","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","1425–1476":"1425–1476","1442–Male":"1442–Surnud","1444–Male":"1444–Surnud","1446–1518":"1446–1518","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1425":"1425","1446":"1446","January 1442":"jaanuar 1442","1400":"1400","1444":"1444","March 1444":"märts 1444","1476":"1476","1442":"1442","ABT. 1425":"umbes 1425","about 1420":"umbes 1420","July 1446":"juuli 1446","1518":"1518"},"fi":{"ABT. 1425–":"noin 1425–Kuollut","1425–Female":"1425–Kuollut","1425–1476":"1425–1476","1442–Male":"1442–Kuollut","1444–Male":"1444–Kuollut","1446–1518":"1446–1518","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","1400–Female":"1400–Kuollut","1425":"1425","1446":"1446","January 1442":"tammikuu 1442","1400":"1